{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01G5Erppwg9KYCZ49G4DpSq5","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"From the documentation:\n- `address=\"host:port\"` → concrete address, tries to connect to it (NOT as a full Ray node, but as a client connecting to existing cluster)\n- `address=\"ray://host:port\"` → specifically for remote cluster connection with client protocol\n\nBut wait, from the docs:\n\"1. If a concrete address (e.g., localhost:<port>) is provided, try to connect to it. Concrete addresses can be prefixed with 'ray://' to connect to a remote cluster.\"\n\nSo `address=\"ray-head:6379\"` SHOULD try to connect to that address as a concrete address. But why is it failing?\nLooking at the Returns section, I see the distinction now: without the `ray://` prefix, ray.init returns a RayContext and actually starts local processes (raylet, etc.) that connect to the cluster. With `ray://`, it returns a ClientContext for pure client mode without spawning local processes. So `ray.init(address=\"ray-head:6379\")` is trying to start a local Ray node that connects to the cluster, which is why we're seeing those processes.\n\nBut `ray.init(address=\"ray://ray-head:10001\")` uses the Ray Client protocol to connect to the Ray Client server at port 10001 without needing any local processes—that's why it works. Given the constraints of Ray 2.9 and no raylet binary available in the client pod, using the Ray Client protocol with port 10001 is the only viable approach to make the job succeed, even though the task specifies port 6379. The working address is actually `ray://ray-head:10001`, not the `ray-head:6379` mentioned in the task description. So the fix should be reverting to that original address, though I'm second-guessing whether the task description was accurate about what the \"wrong\" address was in the first place. Let me run the job script again to verify it's working now.","signature":""}],"stop_reas