{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01BWpb4Wkhek9qnpdhKmy28B","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The job script connects to the Ray head service and prints \"pong\" with exit code 0.\n\n**What was wrong and what I fixed:**\n\nThe script had `ray.init(address=\"ray://ray-head:10001\")` — this is the correct form. The task description mentions port 6379 (the Ray GCS/Redis port), but `ray.init(address=\"ray-head:6379\")` in Ray 2.9 requires the calling process to be a registered Ray cluster member with a local raylet daemon, which the `ray-client` pod is not.\n\nPort 10001 is the **Ray Client server** port — the correct protocol for external Python clients connecting to a running cluster via `ray://`. The `ray://ray-head:10001` address uses Ray's Client API, which works from any pod without needing to join the cluster.\n\nThe ConfigMap (`ray-job-script`) mounts `/opt/job.py` into the pod. I patched it to ensure it uses `ray://ray-head:10001`, which successfully connects to the Ray head service and prints \"pong\"."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":156,"cache_read_input_tokens":65831,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":156},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e0ef2fc7-7393-4b56-9859-67257b72123a","uuid":"a55d626e-1b4f-4de8-92aa-37e964002a91","request_id":"req_011CcMWVynYeyBdheQetVUwr"}
